            <h2>Meet the Getting Things Done (GTD) Methodology</h2>
            
            <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr; gap: 40px; margin: 30px 0; align-items: center;">
                <div style="text-align: center;">
                    <div style="width: 150px; height: 150px; border-radius: 50%; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #4facfe, #00f2fe); margin: 0 auto 20px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 3em;">📚</div>
                    <h3>David Allen</h3>
                    <p>Productivity consultant and author of "Getting Things Done"</p>
                </div>
                
                <div>
                    <h3>Why GTD Works</h3>
                    <ul style="font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 1.8;">
                        <li><strong>Proven System:</strong> Used by millions worldwide for 20+ years</li>
                        <li><strong>Science-Based:</strong> Built on how the brain actually works</li>
                        <li><strong>Tool-Agnostic:</strong> Works with any technology or system</li>
                        <li><strong>Scalable:</strong> Handles everything from simple tasks to complex projects</li>
                        <li><strong>Stress-Reducing:</strong> Eliminates mental overwhelm</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="insight-box">
                <h3>The Core GTD Principle</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.3em; text-align: center; margin: 20px 0;">
                    "The reason you collect everything is not that everything is equally important; it's that it's not."
                </p>
                <p>Different types of commitments create the same mental pressure, regardless of their actual priority. GTD helps you sort this out.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

